                    Work through examples with learners step by step. Circulate during independent practice and provide assistance where needed.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <example xml:id="auto_d4adjzzc">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_efsqfewu">
                Roll a fair six-sided die, what is the probability of rolling either a <m>3</m> or a <m>5</m>?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_kjcqyekr">
                Sample Space
                <md>
                    <mrow>\textbf{S = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6}} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_18n5z79u">
                Favorable Outcomes
                <ul xml:id="auto_kff8jiv5">
                    <li xml:id="auto_cvosnbk1">
                        <p xml:id="auto_1u672i9j">
                            <m>\textbf{P(3)} = \frac{1}{6}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_6m478oxx">
                        <p xml:id="auto_yt36la8i">
                            <m>\textbf{P(5)} = \frac{1}{6}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_0o08ysuq">
                Since rolling a 3 and rolling a 5 are mutually exclusive events;
                <md>
                    <mrow>\textbf{P(3 or 5)} = \textbf{P(3) + P(5)}  </mrow>
                </md>
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \frac{1}{6} + \frac{1}{6} </mrow>
                </md>
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \frac{2}{6} = \frac{1}{3} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_x6j65bie">
                the probability of rolling a <m>3</m> or <m>5</m> is <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> or <m>33.33\%</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_5co0a4l1">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_hirbvhp2">
                A card is drawn from a standard deck of 52 playing cards.
                Let Event A be drawing a Heart and Event B be drawing a Spade.
                Are these events mutually exclusive? Explain
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ctwibgao">
                <ol xml:id="auto_oekrgbe2" marker="a).">
                    <li xml:id="auto_nl362z1z">
                        <p xml:id="auto_coetsnqj">
                            Find <m> \textbf{P(A) and P(B)} </m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_nb98wxz2">
                        <p xml:id="auto_xzb8fhbc">
                            Calculate <m>\textbf{P(A or B)}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_hwmdft1u">
                        <p xml:id="auto_7mt5aiyh">
                            What is <m>\textbf{P}(\textbf{A} \, \cap \, \textbf{B})</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_iw1xxpbv">
                Two events are mutually exclusive if they cannot happen at the same time.
                Since a card cannot be both a Heart and a Spade, the events are mutually exclusive.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_fpvmlwsc">
                <ol xml:id="auto_dqxdboqk">
                    <li xml:id="auto_vhur2lhs">
                        <p xml:id="auto_1it7sfh8">
                            We calculate the probability of drawing a Heart or a Spade.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_n2mcx0tt">
                            Since there are <m>\textbf{13 Hearts}</m> in the deck,
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_i8qxkvba">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \textbf{P(A)} \, = \, \frac{13}{52} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_l947paei">
                            Since there are <m>\textbf{13 Spades}</m> in the deck,
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_4qi5n601">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \textbf{P(B)} \, = \, \frac{13}{52} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_5c7vwh5x">
                        <p xml:id="auto_lpmyts3l">
                            For mutually exclusive events, we use,
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_s16iukqd">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \textbf{P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B)} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_d4ym99p8">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> = \frac{13}{52} + \frac{13}{52} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_r6w6lxz2">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> = \frac{26}{52} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_uyioeoaj">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> = \frac{1}{2} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_7fqzokx6">
                        <p xml:id="auto_6jq9tcfu">
                            Since these events are mutually exclusive, their intersection is zero:
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_3deuh2oy">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \textbf{P} (\textbf{A} \cap \textbf{B}) = 0 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

